#Text=Tupoumoheofo
#Text=Tupoumoheofo was 12th Tu'i Kanokupolu of Tonga , and the only female to ever hold that title .
#Text=She was the principal wife to the Tu'i Tonga though she may have been of higher social rank than him because of her matrilineal descent .

#Text=After a vacancy in the Tu'i Kanokupolu title , she used her status to designated herself successor , reigning on Tongatapu for slightly less than one year starting in perhaps 1792 before being forcibly deposed by her distant relative Tuku’aho .
#Text=Tupoumoheofo retreated to retirement in the northern Tongan Island of Vava’u under the protection of the ' Ulukalala family .
#Text=Family and Social Rank
#Text=In the late 18th century , Tupoumoheofo may have been the highest-ranking person in Tonga due to her matrilineal descent . [ 1 ]
#Text=Her “ mother ’s mother was Tamaha , the sacred eldest daughter of the Tu’i Tonga ’s eldest sister , and thus the person holding the highest rank in Tonga(van der Grijp 538 ) ” .
#Text=She also earned high status through her patrilineal descent as her father was Tupoulahi , the 7th Kanokupolu .
#Text=Tupoumoheofo was a sister of Tu’ihalafatai , the 9th Tu’i Kanokupolu . [ 2 ]

#Text=In the late 1760s , Tupoumoheofo married Tu’i Tonga Paulaho , the 36th Tu'i Tonga , as principal wife ( the moheofo ) , whom she is often considered to have helped in assassinating in 1791 . [ 3 ]
#Text=With her husband Paulaho , Tupoumoheofo had several daughters . [ 4 ]
#Text=Fuanunuiava , the future 38th Tu’i Tonga , is often said also to be a son of this marriage and that obtaining him his future title was one of Tupoumoheofo ’s main goals .

#Text=A genealogy collected by Neil Gunson suggests , however , that Fuanunuiava was not Tupoumoheofo ’s son but instead Paulaho ’s son from his secondary wife , Fokonofo(202 herda ) and therefore Tupoumoheofo would have little reason to push him into power . [ 5 ]
#Text=The Death of Her Husband
#Text=There is some disagreement over when Paulaho was murdered – whether it was 1784 or a decade later . [ 6 ]
#Text=He most likely died in 1791 or 1792 , just before Tupoumoheofo claimed the title of Tu’i Kanokupolu . [ 7 ]

#Text=In an interview by a Spanish sailor years later , Tupoumoheofo claimed to have been a leading participant in an alliance of the Tu’i Kanokupolu lineage that , “ set out from Tonga with some 20 large canoes , putting into the ports of Annamoka [ Nomuka ] and Happai [ Ha’apai ] .
#Text=They passed to Vavao [ Vava’u ] where Paulajo [ Paulaho ] , as the head of his people , received them .
#Text=There was a clash which ended with the death of the latter at the hands of Vuna , after these two leaders fought hand to hand … ” [ 8 ]
#Text=This put her in alliance with Mumui , who , though later her challenger , was a relative of the Tu’i Kanokupolu line .
#Text=The result was to completely debase the power of the Tu’i Tonga line and elevate the Tu’i Kanokupolu line .
#Text=Ascension to Tu'i Kanokupolu
#Text=Around 1791 , the 11th Kanokupolu , Mulikiha’ame’a , gave up his title rather quickly after attaining it . [ 9 ]
#Text=Some surmise that either he lost influence , [ 10 ] he obtained a different title , that Mumui and Tuku’aho forced him out , or that Tupoumoheofo herself instigated the change .

#Text=Though the next Kanokupolu would be officially voted on by the Ha’a Ngata chiefs , [ 11 ] ancestral protectors of the Kanokupolu line in Hihifo , Tongatapu , the decision was really Tupoumoheofo ’s because of her rank .
#Text=Mumui , a powerful elder chief on Tongatapu , expected to receive the title .
#Text=He shared ancestry with Tupoumoheofo through Ma’afu’out’itonga , the sixth Kanokupolu , but his was of a lesser line . [ 12 ]
#Text=Tuku’aho , Mumui ’s politically ambitious son and then governor of ‘ Eua , strongly supported his father ’s claim with hopes of securing power for their line . [ 13 ]
#Text=Tupoumoheofo , however , did the unexpected by naming herself as Kanokupolu .
#Text=She , “ went to Hihifo , put a ta’ovala mat about her waist , and sat with her back to the koka tree beneath which the installation of the Tu’i Kanokupolu took place .
#Text=Then she came back and declared herself Tu’i Kanokupolu . ” [ 14 ]
#Text=This appropriateness of ascension is controversial among historians .
#Text=Early European missionaries in Tonga labeled her act as , “ subversive ” , “ tyrannical ” , “ odious in the extreme ” [ 15 ] and an anthropologist has considered it “ unrightful " [ 16 ]
